**Indoor Cycling Playlist Designer**

Requirements Specification

Version 1.0  ·  June 2, 2026

# Contents

# 1. Overview

A web application that helps indoor cycling instructors design class playlists, integrated with Spotify. The instructor builds a playlist as an ordered sequence of cue-based segments, tags individual songs to a cue type, and marks the precise moments within each song where an action (such as a jump sequence) occurs.

The application is mobile-first: an instructor will frequently set up and adjust playlists on a phone, including beside the bike. Mobile is treated as a first-class, likely primary, experience.

## 1.1 The Five Cues

Every song is assigned to exactly one cue category, and the playlist is composed of segments of these cues:

- Jumps

- Climbs

- Sprints

- Choreo

- Flat

## 1.2 Scope of This Version (v1)

This document specifies version 1. Persistence is limited to a single session (no database, no accounts beyond Spotify authentication). Items deferred to later versions are listed in Section 7.

# 2. Core User Flow

- The user authenticates with Spotify via OAuth. A Spotify Premium account is required.

- The user finds songs two ways: by searching Spotify and by browsing their own Spotify library and playlists.

- The user tags each song with exactly one cue (Jumps, Climbs, Sprints, Choreo, or Flat).

- Selecting a cue displays the list of songs the user has tagged with that cue. The list may be empty or populated depending on prior tagging.

- Within any song, the user marks one or more in-track sequences — time spans identifying when an action occurs (see Section 3).

- The user builds a playlist as an ordered sequence of cue segments (for example: Flat → Climb → Sprint → Climb → Flat), placing songs into the segment for each cue.

- Each segment displays its total duration.

- The user saves the finished playlist back to their Spotify account.

# 3. In-track Sequences

A sequence is a labeled time span inside a single song that marks exactly when an action happens (for example, when the jump sequence begins and ends). Sequences let the instructor know, mid-class, precisely where the action is in each track.

## 3.1 Definition

- A sequence is a span with both a start time and an end time (not a single point).

- A song may have multiple sequences.

- Sequences within a song must not overlap. Creating a sequence that overlaps an existing one is rejected by validation.

- Sequences sort naturally by start time.

- Each sequence carries an optional free-text note.

- A sequence inherits its cue from the parent song; it does not store its own cue. Because a song belongs to exactly one cue, all of that song’s sequences belong to that same cue.

## 3.2 Marking Timestamps

The user sets a sequence by playing the track and tapping a button to capture the current playhead position — a “Mark Start” / “Mark End” pattern. This requires real-time playback position from the Spotify Web Playback SDK, which in turn requires a Premium account. (See Section 5 for the platform constraint.)

# 4. Cue Reassignment

A song’s cue can be changed at any time, moving it from one cue category to another (for example, Climbs → Sprints). When a song is reassigned:

- All of its in-track sequences (timestamps and notes) are preserved unchanged.

- The song leaves its previous cue’s list and appears under the new cue, carrying its sequences with it.

This is structurally trivial because sequences carry only timestamps and a note and inherit the song’s current cue — reassignment is a single change to the song’s cue field with no effect on its sequences. Note: a sequence’s free-text note may reference the old cue’s vocabulary after a move; this is left as the user’s responsibility and requires no system action.

# 5. Spotify Integration & Platform Constraints

## 5.1 Authentication & Scopes

The application uses Spotify OAuth and requires a registered Spotify Developer app with a configured redirect URI, plus a backend to hold the access token securely. This is not a frontend-only project.

Required scopes:

- user-library-read — read the user’s saved tracks and library

- playlist-read-private — read the user’s private playlists

- playlist-modify-private and/or playlist-modify-public — save the finished playlist back

- streaming and related scopes — for full-track playback via the Web Playback SDK

## 5.2 Playback

Full-track playback uses the Spotify Web Playback SDK and requires the listener to have Spotify Premium. v1 requires Premium and does not provide a non-Premium fallback. This requirement supports the Mark Start / Mark End timestamp feature in Section 3.2.

## 5.3 BPM Data — Important Constraint

Spotify deprecated its Audio Features endpoint (the source of tempo/BPM data). Only apps approved before November 27, 2024 retain access; newly registered apps receive a 403 Forbidden response. Because this project requires a new Spotify app, Spotify-provided BPM is not available.

BPM is therefore deferred from v1. See Section 6 for the required extensibility approach so BPM can be added later from a third-party source.

## 5.4 Audio Previews

Spotify’s 30-second preview availability has become unreliable and should not be assumed. The application relies on full playback (Premium) rather than previews.

# 6. BPM — Deferred but Designed-For

BPM is out of scope for v1, but the architecture must be built so that BPM can be added later from a third-party provider (such as GetSongBPM or Cyanite) without reworking the data model or core logic. Three provisions are required:

- Reserve the field. Keep an optional, nullable bpm field on the Song model. It is always empty in v1; this avoids a future migration.

- Isolate the source behind an interface. Route all BPM retrieval through a single swappable provider (conceptually, a BpmProvider with a method such as getBpm(song) returning a number or null). In v1 this is a no-op returning null. Later, a real implementation is swapped in without touching UI or playlist code.

- Degrade gracefully. Any UI location that would show BPM must render nothing (or a subtle placeholder) when BPM is null, rather than breaking. This display path is built in v1 even though it always shows empty.

Explicitly NOT built in v1: any third-party API call, credentials for a BPM service, or manual BPM-entry UI. Adding BPM later must require no changes to the data model or core playlist logic.

# 7. Data Model

Single session; no database. State is held in memory for the duration of the session.

## 7.1 Song

| **Field** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| **id** | Unique identifier. |
| **title** | Track title. |
| **artist** | Track artist. |
| **durationMs** | Track length in milliseconds. |
| **spotifyUri** | Spotify URI for playback and saving. |
| **cue** | Exactly one of: Jumps, Climbs, Sprints, Choreo, Flat. |
| **bpm** | Optional / nullable. Always empty in v1; reserved for future BPM support. |
| **sequences[]** | Ordered by start time, non-overlapping. See Sequence. |

## 7.2 Sequence

| **Field** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| **startMs** | Start of the span, in milliseconds. |
| **endMs** | End of the span, in milliseconds. Must be greater than startMs. |
| **note** | Optional free-text note. |

**Invariants: **cue is inherited from the parent Song and is not stored on the sequence; no two sequences on the same song may overlap.

## 7.3 Segment

A single step in the playlist.

| **Field** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| **cue** | The cue type for this segment. |
| **songs[]** | Ordered list of songs in this segment. |
| **totalDuration** | Computed sum of the segment’s song durations. |

## 7.4 Playlist

| **Field** | **Description** |
| --- | --- |
| **segments[]** | Ordered sequence of cue segments that make up the class playlist. |

# 8. UX & Platform Requirements

Mobile-first responsive design: laid out for narrow phone screens first, scaling up to desktop — not desktop-first scaled down. The interface must be clean, uncluttered, and easy to learn, prioritizing the three core flows (tagging songs, building the cue-segment playlist, and marking in-track sequences).

Touch-optimized controls throughout, with particular attention to:

- Mark Start / Mark End buttons must be large, thumb-reachable, and hard to misfire, since the user taps them while the song plays and their attention is on the music.

- Ordering playlist segments and songs must use a touch-reliable method (e.g. well-sized drag handles, or up/down / move actions) rather than fiddly desktop-style dragging.

- Cue selection (five categories) suits large tappable cards or a segmented control rather than a dropdown.

- Spotify search and library browsing are list-heavy and must remain readable and scrollable on a narrow screen with no horizontal overflow.

# 9. Out of Scope (v1)

- Automatic tagging of songs by audio features.

- Cross-session saving, accounts, or a database (beyond Spotify authentication).

- Multiple cues per song (a song belongs to exactly one cue).

- Sequences with their own cue distinct from the song (sequences inherit the song’s cue).

- BPM display and any BPM data source (deferred; architecture must reserve for it per Section 6).

- Non-Premium playback fallback.

- Audio previews.

